definition.value: In plants, lateral growth (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0080190) run is along the medial/radial axis (from medial to radial) [RW].  Also applies to radially symmetrical animals such as sea urchins, cnidarians [PM] or applies to more-or-less cylindrical body parts in animals, like limbs.

value.value: An axis that extends from the oral opening to the furthest point in an organism that is directly opposite.

An axis that extends from the animal end of an egg or early embryo to the opposite, vegetal end. In animals with yolk-bearing eggs, the vegetal end is the yolk bearing pole. (pertains to animals only - both vertebrate and invertebrate embryos).

label.value: apical-basal axis relative to direction of growth

value.value: An axis of a plant structure that is determined by the direction of apical growth, either by an apical meristem or an apical cell. Apical is toward the direction of apical growth: toward the tip of a growing shoot axis, root, thallus, or non-vascular leaf. Basal is away from the direction of apical growth: toward the root-shoot junction in the case of the primary root or stem, toward the primary root or stem for higher order roots or branches, toward the point of attachment for non-vascular leaves, and toward the original point of growth (as determined in the embryo) for thalli.

definition.value: Plant structures that do not grow from an apical meristem, such as vascular leaves or petals, should be described using the proximal-distal axis. The proximal-distal axis may also be used for branches or lateral roots, and, in those cases, is concordant with the apical-basal axis.

value.value: Anatomical plane that is perpendicular to a radial plane.
